<br>
Second, hindsight is always 20/20, and I think it is quite fair to say that given any decent college level textbook to peruse, most (though of course not all) of history's leaders would have done things differently.  <br>
<br>
Third, whoever said the Boston Tea Party wasn't terrorism- read up a little more on the incident.  The Colonists ended up using violence on a wide scale to prevent the implimentation of the Stamp tax and Tea Act, to include tarring and feathering and beatings.  In response the British used prison terms, impressment, flogging, hanging and of course, the so-called &quot;Boston Massacre.&quot;<br>
<br>
Fourth, the original topic of this thread was &quot;are there any forms of terrorism that are good.&quot;  I submit that until we have working definitions of &quot;terrorism&quot; and &quot;good&quot; then the answer is far more subjective than need be.<br>
<br>
Fifth, and finally, as far as Hiroshima and Nagasaki, the fact that many high American officials opposed it on humanitarian grounds, and said so, in many cases publicly, is a matter of record.  In fact, the whole strategic bombing campaign was harshly criticised, in both the UK and the US, throughout the Second World War.  The fact remains however, that in terms of moral use, the Allies were in fact only retaliating to previous bombings of civilians by Italian, German and Japanese forces.  That the Allies were able to do so on a far, far greater scale only increases the impression that the Axis were a bunch of n00bs who had no clue.  They forgot to /con the US before they typed /d = ).  I think the fact that there was (and to this day is) a debate on the topic shows that the Allies undertook this campaign reluctantly (except the Air Forces involved, to some extent) and mainly because, AT THE TIME, they saw bombing civilians as both necessary to national survival and morally justifiable by the limitations of the technology they were using to strike at the enemies military potential.  The choice was to kill civilians, and on a large scale, or do nothing at all.  They chose to strike.  <br>
<br>
P.S, Hiroshima was one of the larger IJN bases, and both Hiroshima and Nagasaki had both large garrisions and, like all Japanese cities at the time, extensive sub-contracting work spread throught the entire city areas.<br>
<br>
